31
00:01:16,120 --> 00:01:17,840
and you've heard it measured in deltas.

32
00:01:18,460 --> 00:01:21,080
Delta measures the change in the actual options

33
00:01:21,080 --> 00:01:23,860
price for each plus or minus $1 move

34
00:01:23,860 --> 00:01:24,620
in the underlying.

35
00:01:25,220 --> 00:01:27,780
So say you have Apple for example, for

36
00:01:27,780 --> 00:01:30,580
each plus or minus $1 move that Apple

37
00:01:30,580 --> 00:01:33,380
moves the delta tells you how much that

38
00:01:33,380 --> 00:01:34,180
option will move.

39
00:01:34,260 --> 00:01:36,540
So say a delta 50 options will move

40
00:01:36,540 --> 00:01:39,660
$50 for every plus or minus $1 move.

41
00:01:40,220 --> 00:01:42,680
Now in this case you also have to

42
00:01:42,680 --> 00:01:45,120
measure that the delta today is not going

43
00:01:45,120 --> 00:01:46,960
to be the same as the delta tomorrow.

44
00:01:47,460 --> 00:01:49,940
You have this concept called delta decay and

45
00:01:49,940 --> 00:01:50,980
the delta changes.

46
00:01:51,620 --> 00:01:53,980
Now the rate at which this delta changes

47
00:01:53,980 --> 00:01:55,800
is measured through gamma.

48
00:01:56,380 --> 00:01:58,800
Gamma measures the change in the options delta

49
00:01:58,800 --> 00:02:01,580
for each plus or minus $1 stock move.

50
00:02:02,280 --> 00:02:06,020
